<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4581283" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4581283" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4581283/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="2696" startId="26.[125,185,1611,1630]" targetBox="[171,1128,236,1574]" targetPageId="26">
<paragraph blockId="26.[125,1173,1610,1683]" pageId="26" pageNumber="2696">
Figure 11. (A–C) 
<taxonomicName authority="Branch &amp; Hayward, 2005" authorityName="Branch &amp; Hayward" authorityYear="2005" box="[301,494,1611,1630]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Microporellidae" genus="Fenestrulina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="26" pageNumber="2696" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="pumicosa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[301,494,1611,1630]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="2696">Fenestrulina pumicosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[502,580,1611,1630]" pageId="26" pageNumber="2696" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, SAM A27362: (A) ovicelled autozooid, X70; (B) autozooids, X45; (C) primary orifice and ascopore, X110. (D–G) 
<taxonomicName authority="Branch &amp; Hayward, 2005" authorityName="Branch &amp; Hayward" authorityYear="2005" box="[662,888,1637,1656]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Microporellidae" genus="Microporella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="26" pageNumber="2696" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="mandibulata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[662,888,1637,1656]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="2696">Microporella mandibulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[898,977,1637,1656]" pageId="26" pageNumber="2696" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, SAM A27554: (D) autozooid, X100; (E) ascopore, X180; (F) avicularium, X180; (G) avicularium with long mandible, X150.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="27.[138,1185,185,597]" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697">
Colony encrusting on rock, forming small, unilaminar patches. Autozooids oval to hexagonal, convex, separated by thin ridges marking the vertical walls; 0.55–0.6X 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.25" metricValueMax="4.5" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697" unit="mm" value="0.425" valueMax="0.45" valueMin="0.4">0.4– 0.45 mm</quantity>
. Frontal shield irregularly spinous, the ‘‘spines’’ representing projections of the frontal calcification; imperforate centrally, but with large, rounded areolar pores closely spaced around the margin. Primary orifice slightly wider than long, 0.1X 
<quantity box="[1014,1119,315,339]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697" unit="mm" value="0.09">0.09 mm</quantity>
, with straight proximal border. Six short, cylindrical oral spines present. Ascopore close to the proximal border of the orifice, separated from it by a distance equivalent to one-quarter orifice length; narrowly crescentic, with a toothed rim, set within a shallow dish, ca 
<quantity box="[138,240,444,468]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697" unit="mm" value="0.05">0.05 mm</quantity>
diameter; a thick, raised peristome, with coarsely crenulated edge, extends proximally between the bases of the proximal spine pair, enclosing the ascopore. One or two large pores present within the peristome, close to the proximo-lateral corners of the orifice, and equally large pores are present around the distal end of the autozooid. Ovicell not found.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[138,251,654,678]" box="[138,251,654,678]" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697">
<emphasis box="[138,251,654,678]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697">Etymology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[138,1185,703,759]" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697">
Latin, 
<emphasis box="[221,308,703,727]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697">spinosus</emphasis>
, thorny, with reference to the spinous frontal shield calcification of the zooids.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[138,233,816,840]" box="[138,233,816,840]" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697">
<emphasis box="[138,233,816,840]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[138,1185,864,1373]" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697">
The rather robust frontal calcification, with deep areolar pores, and the flaring peristome enclosing the ascopore, suggest that this new species is more appropriately accommodated within 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Neviani" authorityYear="1895" box="[222,349,929,953]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Microporellidae" genus="Calloporina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[222,349,929,953]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697">Calloporina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jullien" authorityYear="1888" box="[424,557,929,953]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Microporellidae" genus="Fenestrulina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[424,557,929,953]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697">Fenestrulina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, although the distinction between the two genera is perhaps becoming less clear. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Neviani" authorityYear="1895" box="[478,605,961,985]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Microporellidae" genus="Calloporina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[478,605,961,985]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697">Calloporina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized by a thickly calcified ovicell, with only a narrow area of entooecium exposed frontally. Most species bear adventitious avicularia, and have large marginal areolar pores. However, in 
<taxonomicName authority="Hayward and Ryland, 1990" authorityName="Hayward and Ryland" authorityYear="1990" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Microporellidae" genus="Calloporina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="patagonica">
<emphasis box="[926,1185,1026,1050]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697">Calloporina patagonica</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Hayward PJ &amp; Ryland JS" box="[138,459,1058,1082]" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697" pagination="1263 - 1287" refId="ref12520" refString="Hayward PJ, Ryland JS. 1990. Some Antarctic and Subantarctic species of Microporellidae (Bryozoa: Cheilostomata). Journal of Natural History 24: 1263 - 1287." type="journal article" year="1990">Hayward and Ryland, 1990</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
avicularia are only sparsely present and the ovicell has a broad frontal area of exposed entooecium, and rather resembles that of 
<taxonomicName authority="Branch &amp; Hayward, 2005" authorityName="Branch &amp; Hayward" authorityYear="2005" box="[902,1143,1091,1115]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Microporellidae" genus="Fenestrulina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="pumicosa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[902,1143,1091,1115]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697">Fenestrulina pumicosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="27" pageNumber="2697" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(below). The thick peristomial calcification seen in 
<taxonomicName authority="Branch &amp; Hayward, 2005" authorityName="Branch &amp; Hayward" authorityYear="2005" box="[789,902,1123,1147]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Microporellidae" genus="Calloporina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="spinosa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[789,902,1123,1147]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697">C. spinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[909,1000,1123,1147]" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is also a feature of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hayward and Ryland" authorityYear="1990" box="[173,330,1155,1179]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Microporellidae" genus="Calloporina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="patagonica">
<emphasis box="[173,192,1155,1179]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[212,330,1155,1179]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697">patagonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Further material of this new species is required before its taxonomic affinity can be confidently established. It is apparent, however, that the systematics of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jullien" authorityYear="1888" box="[138,271,1220,1244]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Microporellidae" genus="Fenestrulina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[138,271,1220,1244]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697">Fenestrulina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Neviani" authorityYear="1895" box="[291,417,1220,1244]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Microporellidae" genus="Calloporina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[291,417,1220,1244]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697">Calloporina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and related genera in the southern hemisphere are in need of review. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Neviani" authorityYear="1895" box="[229,356,1252,1276]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Microporellidae" genus="Calloporina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[229,356,1252,1276]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697">Calloporina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was introduced for a Miocene fossil, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Reuss, 1848)" baseAuthorityName="Reuss" baseAuthorityYear="1848" box="[798,1100,1252,1276]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Microporellidae" genus="Calloporina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="decorata">
<emphasis box="[798,924,1252,1276]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697">C. decorata</emphasis>
(Reuss, 1848)
</taxonomicName>
, that is said to be extant, though rare, in the Mediterranean (
<bibRefCitation author="Zabala M &amp; Maluquer P" box="[744,1065,1284,1308]" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697" pagination="1 - 294" refId="ref12946" refString="Zabala M, Maluquer P. 1988. Illustrated keys for the classification of Mediterranean Bryozoa. Treballs del Museu de Zoologia, Barcelona 4: 1 - 294." type="journal article" year="1988">Zabala and Maluquer 1988</bibRefCitation>
). With the exception of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hayward and Ryland" authorityYear="1990" box="[292,447,1317,1341]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Microporellidae" genus="Calloporina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="patagonica">
<emphasis box="[292,447,1317,1341]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697">C. patagonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the genus is otherwise known from the western Pacific, from 
<collectingCountry box="[138,203,1349,1373]" name="Japan" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697">Japan</collectingCountry>
to Australasia, and from Tertiary deposits of 
<collectingCountry box="[742,846,1349,1373]" name="Australia" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697">Australia</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[907,1068,1349,1373]" name="New Zealand" pageId="27" pageNumber="2697">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
